Part I - Ford GoBike System Data¶

by David Okpare¶

Introduction¶

This document explores a dataset containing information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

# calculate distance covered in km
bike_rides['distance_covered'] = bike_rides.apply(lambda x: geopy.distance.distance((x.start_station_latitude, x.start_station_latitude), (x.end_station_latitude, x.end_station_latitude)).km, axis=1)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183,412 individual bike rides with 16 features. Most features have the correct datatype and numeric in nature, but start_time, end_time, start_station_id, end_station_id and member_birth_year have incorrect datatypes. The dataset also features categorical variables (user_type, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip).

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out the time and distance covered on average by subscribers and customers.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that the start_time and end_time will have the strongest effect on calculating the trip's average durarion. And the start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_latitude and end_station_longitude will help determine the average distance covered.

def plot_hour_kde(col_name, title, hue=None):
    """
    Plots a KDE to visualize the hourly distribution of observations.
    """
    sb.set(rc={'figure.figsize': (12,8)})
    g = sb.kdeplot(data=bike_rides, x=col_name, shade=True, hue=hue)
    # set xticks to hourly range
    g.set_xticks(range(24))
    g.set_xticklabels(list(range(24)))
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel("Hour")
    plt.show()
In [20]:
plot_hour_kde('start_time_hour', "Rides commencement time by Hour")

The values in this plot corresponds to the number of rides started at different hours of the day. Majority of rides happen between 7 a.m. to 9 a.m. and 4 p.m. to 6 p.m. These are also the most common starting and closing hours for offices and schools.

In [21]:
plot_hour_kde('end_time_hour', "Rides completion time by Hour")

The number of rides concluded at various hours of the day is plot above.Similarly to the ride starting hour, the rides ends between the hours of 8 a.m. to 9 a.m and 6 p.m (18:00) to 7 p.m (19:00). Based on this, we could assume that most rides end within an hour or covered within a short distance.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The dataset contained members born before 1919, this could have been a data entry error. I eliminated those members from the analysis.

In [40]:
def plot_facetgrid(df, col, x, y):
    """
    Plot a FacetGrid with stripplot for a dataframe to display discrete values.
    """
    g = sb.FacetGrid(data=df, col=col, height=8)
    g.map(sb.stripplot, x, y, size=2, jitter=0.35, order=None)
    plt.show()
In [41]:
plot_facetgrid(bike_rides.query('duration_min<duration_min.quantile(0.99)'), 'user_type', 'start_time_day', 'duration_min')

The plot above shows a daily distribution of time taken for each rides per members. The observation above shows that rides tend take longer duration on Day 6 (Sunday) for both Customers and Subscribers.

The time it takes Subscribers each day to complete a ride is sparsely distributed compared to the duration it takes Customers each day.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Subscribers typically cover longer distances in shorter time span than Customer.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Yes, shared bike trips on Tuesday and Wednesday are typically shorted than the rest.

Conclusions¶

Drawing on the observations found in the charts, these are some of the insights we can understand on the FordBike 2019 data.

Subscribers mostly take rides between 7am to 9am and 4pm to 6pm while Customers have an almost steady increase in rides between 7am and 6pm.

Subscribers also cover longer distances than Customers. Both members take longer rides on Sunday.
